 CG, Pierce RH, Le MH, Algazi AP, Daud AI, Pai SI, Zippelius A, Weissleder R, Pittet MJ |title= Successful Anti-PD-1 Cancer Immunotherapy Requires T Cell-Dendritic Cell Crosstalk Involving the Cytokines IFN-\u03b3 and IL-12. |journal= Immunity |volume=49|pages=1-14 |year =2018 |pmid= 30552023 | pmc= 6301092  |doi= 10.1016/j.immuni.2018.09.024 |url=}}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Zilionis R, Engblom C, Pfirschke C, Savova V, Zemmour D, Saatcioglu HD, Krishnan I, Maroni G, Meyerovitz CV, Kerwin CM, Choi S, Richards WG, De Rienzo A, Tenen DG, Bueno R, Levantini E, Pittet MJ, Klein AM |title= Single-Cell Transcriptomics of Human and Mouse Lung Cancers Reveals Conserved Myeloid Populations across Individuals and Species |journal= Immunity |volume= 50 |issue= 5 |pages= 1317-1334.e10 |year=2019 |pmid= 30979687 | pmc= 6620049 |doi= 10.1016/j.immuni.2019.03.009}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{url|https://csb.mgh.harvard.edu/pittet|Lab webpage}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pittet, Mikael}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:University of Lausanne alumni]]\n[[Category:Swiss emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Harvard Medical School faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lausanne]]\n[[Category:Swiss immunologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swiss scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=September 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Mikael Pittet\n|box_width         = \n|image             = Mikael_Pittet.jpg\n|caption           = Mikael Pittet\n|birth_date        =\n|residence         =\n|citizenship       =\n|nationality       =\n|ethnicity         =\n|field             = [[Clinical Research]], [[Immune System]], [[Cancer Immunotherapy]], [[Molecular Imaging]]\n|work_institutions = [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], [[Harvard Medical School]]\n|alma_mater        =\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         =\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        =\n|influenced        =\n|prizes            =\n|religion          =\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n\n'''Mikael Pittet''' is a [[Swiss]] research scientist.\n\n==Biography==\nMikael J. Pittet (born May 23, 1975 in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland) is a Professor at [[Harvard Medical School]], Senior Faculty of the Center for Systems Biology (CSB) at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] (MGH) and Director of the CSB Cancer Immunology Program.\n\nMikael Pittet completed his PhD thesis in Immunology at the [[Ludwig Institute for Cancer Research]] and graduated from [[University of Lausanne]] in 2001. Following his degrees, Pittet moved to [[Boston]] (USA) where he pursued post-doctoral research at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] (MGH), [[Harvard Medical School]] (HMS) and [[Dana-Farber Cancer Institute]] (DFCI). Pittet became Assistant Professor at HMS in 2006, Associate Professor in 2013, and Professor in 2019 (Department of Radiology). Pittet was named Samana Cay MGH Research Scholar in 2015 and appointed Director of the CSB Cancer Immunology Program in 2016. Pittet is a member of the [[Dana-Farber/Harvard Cancer Center]] and [http://www.hms.harvard.edu/dms/immunology/fac/Pittet.php Immunology Program at Harvard Medical School].\n\nPittet is based at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]]. He is a faculty member of the Department of Radiology and of the MGH Research Institute. He serves on the editorial board of the journals ''Cell Stress''<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.cell-stress.com/about-us/editorial-board/|title=Editorial Board|journal=Cell Stress}}</ref> and ''Cancer Immunology Research''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cancerimmunolres.aacrjournals.org/site/misc/edboard.xhtml|title=Editorial Board - Cancer Immunology Research|website=cancerimmunolres.aacrjournals.org}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nPittet is a widely cited researcher<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=Dh0LHP0AAAAJ|title=Pittet Mikael - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com}}</ref> in [[cancer immunology]] and [[cancer immunotherapy]], especially in the fields of [[Innate immune system|innate]] and [[adaptive immunity]]. His research focuses on uncovering how the immune system controls cancer and other diseases and how it can be harnessed for therapy<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nm0917-1006|title=Uncovering cancer: How enlisting T cells can boost the power of immunotherapy|journal=Nature Medicine | doi=10.1038/nm0917-1006}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/features/macrophages-play-a-double-role-in-cancer-29875|title=Macrophages Play a Double Role in Cancer |journal=The Scientist}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-017-07831-3|title=Cancer-promoting cells are bred in the bone |journal=Nature | doi=10.1038/d41586-017-07831-3}}</ref>. He is known for utilizing [[molecular imaging]] to track immune cells and drugs directly in vivo<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://immunology.sciencemag.org/content/2/12/eaan8155.full|title= PD-1 blockade: It\u2019s what\u2019s for dinner|journal=Science Immunology | doi=10.1126/sciimmunol.aan8155}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://cancerdiscovery.aacrjournals.org/content/early/2017/06/14/2159-8290.CD-NB2017-081|title= Macrophages Promote Resistance to Checkpoint Inhibitors |journal=Cancer Discovery}}</ref>. Pittet\u2019s work has identified how cancers are regulated by various immune cells, including [[cytotoxic T cells]], [[regulatory T cells]], [[macrophages]], [[monocytes]], [[neutrophils]], and [[dendritic cells]]. These cells are considered as drug targets in [[cancer immunotherapy]].\n\n==Publications==\nPittet has authored over 140 publications in peer-reviewed journals and contributed to several textbooks. His work has been cited >25,000 times and he has an [[h-index]] of 75.\n\n==Awards and honors==\nPittet\u2019s work has been honored with the 2015 Samana Cay MGH Research Scholarship Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.massgeneral.org/research/support/research-scholars.aspx|title=Mass General Research Scholars - Massachusetts General Hospital, Boston, MA|website=www.massgeneral.org}}</ref> the 2016 Robert Wenner Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.krebsliga.ch/forschung/auszeichnungen/robert-wenner-preis/|title=Robert Wenner-Preis|website=Krebsliga}}</ref> the 2016 Distinguished Investigator Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acadrad.org/description-of-award/|title=Description of Award \u2013 The Academy for Radiology & Biomedical Imaging Research|website=www.acadrad.org}}</ref> from the Academy of Radiology Research, and the 2017 MGH Mentoring Award. Pittet is recognized as a Highly Cited Researcher based on his multiple papers that rank in the top 1% by citations across fields and during the last decade<ref>{{cite web|url= https://hcr.clarivate.com/#freeText%3Dpittet%26categories%3Dcross-field|title=Highly Cited Researchers 2019|website=hcr.clarivate.com}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Pittet MJ, Valmori D, Dunbar PR, Speiser DE, Li\u00e9nard D, Lejeune F, Fleischhauer K, Cerundolo V, Cerottini JC, Romero P |title= High frequencies of naive Melan-A/MART-1-specific CD8(+) T cells in a large proportion of human histocompatibility leukocyte antigen (HLA)-A2 individuals |journal= J Exp Med |volume= 190 |issue= 5 |pages= 705\u201315 |year=1999 |pmid= 10477554 | pmc= 2195613 |doi=10.1084/jem.190.5.705}}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Zippelius A, Batard P, Rubio-Godoy V, Bioley G, Lienard D, Lejeune F, Rimoldi D, Guillaume P, Meidenbauer N, Mackensen A, Rufer N, Lubenow N, Speiser D, Cerottini J, Romero P, Pittet MJ |title= Effector function of human tumor-specific CD8 T cells in melanoma lesions: a state of local functional tolerance |journal= Cancer Res |volume=64 |issue=|pages= 2865\u201373 |year=2004 |pmid= 15087405 |doi=10.1158/0008-5472.can-03-3066}}\n* {{cite journal |vauthors=Mempel TR, Pittet MJ, Khazaie K,